entry.title: [CrOS Cellular] Add timeout to NetworkSmsHandler receive queue
entry.content:
Fix NetworkSmsHandler receive queue getting stuck if an SMS' GetAll()

call hangs. This can happen in cases where a multi-part SMS is sent

and one of the parts is removed (for reasons unfound currently). This

will cause the message to never change from status Receiving to

complete, causing the NetworkSmsHandler queue to get stuck. If the

queue is stuck, any SMSes after it in the queue will never be processed,

shown in the UI, and deleted.

entry.title: Revert "Async[*] capture of a viz::Surface."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 06165426690774355004ccdff9a40c2cf0938889.



Reason for revert: https://crbug.com/1442953



Original change's description:

> Async[*] capture of a viz::Surface.

>

> Context: we are building a new feature that requires to capture the

> current surface before the navigation destroys it. We plan to install

> the capture code inside the NavigationRequest right before the

> navigation commits.

>

> [*] To clarify: RWHV->CopyFromSurface does not block, but it cannot

> guarantee the Surface is copiable by the time the GPU generates the

> bitmap during the next draw (e.g., navigation commits before the next

> draw). Prior to this CL, we must block the navigation and wait for the

> GPU before we can proceed. This CL changes that.

>

> We cannot incur any delay to the navigation thus the capture cannot

> block the UI thread. For this we are proposing:

> - Make sure the surface-of-interest's ID is reachable from the root, via

> LayerTreeHost::AddSurfaceRange. The is done before the navigation

> commits.

> - After the GPU has generated the bitmap, call

> LayerTreeHost::RemoveSurfaceRange to remove the surface's ID. This

> ensures that the SurfaceID which corresponds to the CompositorFrame

> for the last committed entry remains cached in the GPU process until

> it has been captured.

>

entry.title: Store frame site in NIK for building nonced CookiePartitionKeys
entry.content:
This is necessary because nonced CPKs use the frame site of the NIK

instead of the top-frame site. This is done to match StorageKey's

implementation of nonced partitions, since they need to be consistent

entry.title: Async[*] capture of a viz::Surface.
entry.content:
Context: we are building a new feature that requires to capture the

current surface before the navigation destroys it. We plan to install

the capture code inside the NavigationRequest right before the

navigation commits.



[*] To clarify: RWHV->CopyFromSurface does not block, but it cannot

guarantee the Surface is copiable by the time the GPU generates the

bitmap during the next draw (e.g., navigation commits before the next

draw). Prior to this CL, we must block the navigation and wait for the

GPU before we can proceed. This CL changes that.



We cannot incur any delay to the navigation thus the capture cannot

block the UI thread. For this we are proposing:

- Make sure the surface-of-interest's ID is reachable from the root, via

LayerTreeHost::AddSurfaceRange. The is done before the navigation

commits.

- After the GPU has generated the bitmap, call

LayerTreeHost::RemoveSurfaceRange to remove the surface's ID. This

ensures that the SurfaceID which corresponds to the CompositorFrame

for the last committed entry remains cached in the GPU process until

it has been captured.

entry.title: Print Preview: Fix duplex default mode set by policy
entry.content:
Default duplex mode sometimes works incorrectly. The exact combinations

of non-working policies can be found in the attached issue.



There are a couple changes in this CL:

- If the allowed duplex mode is DUPLEX, then we use the default duplex

mode as the default value if it's consistent (i.e. the default duplex

mode should be either SHORT_EDGE or LONG_EDGE).

- Duplex policy defaults now always override printing destination

defaults.

- Indicate that the duplexShortEdge (i.e. the two-sided selection box)

can never be restricted by a policy. That's valid because if one of

the two-sided options is available by the policy, then the other one

should also be available.



Note that the duplex policies (PrintingAllowedDuplexModes and

PrintingDuplexDefault) are only supported on ChromeOS, thus the changes

in this CL are applicable to ChromeOS only. Also explicitly restricting

handling color and PIN related policies to ChromeOS only. These policies

are already only available on ChromeOS, so this change will not affect

the behavior.

entry.title: PSCS: Change when WebContentsDestroyed is called
entry.content:
In a scenario where a SiteDataObserver is also a WebContentsUserData

[1], we could run into problems while cleaning up on WebContents

destruction. In this situation, ~SiteDataObserver is called during

WebContentsUserData destruction before ~PSCS::WebContentsHandler. We

try looking up PSCS from the WebContents in ~SiteDataObserver, but at

this point, the WCUD map is empty [2], and the lookup will fail, even

though the PSCS::WebContentsHandler object itself is still alive. This

could mean that the observer can't deregister itself from

PSCS::WebContentsHolder and we have a dangling pointer.



This CL moves some of this clean up to

WebContentsObserver::WebContentsDestroyed, which is called before

WebContentsUserData is cleared and SiteDataObserver can now lookup

PSCS::WebContentsHandler.



[1] https://crrev.com/c/4489564/9 attempted to make a WCUD a SiteDataObserver



[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:base/supports_user_data.cc;l=123;drc=e0e0d24aaa54727dc0a8bc4b159ccdf80d3f5d8d

entry.title: [CodeHealth] Simplify dns resolution routines across network_diagnostics
entry.content:
This CL introduces the following changes:

* Routines that implement HostResolverClientBase are switched to a

callback-based model via network::SimpleHostResolver;

* Various FakeHostResolver/FakeNetworkContext/DnsResult classes and

structs are now united under one roof in fake_network_context.h;

* Unit tests are upgraded to base::test::TestFuture<>.



Some minor things also present in the CL:

* Post-resolution processing is simplified: for DnsQueryType::A |result|

equal to net::OK guarantees that |resolved_addresses| are populated.

* Some tests that populate |resolved_addresses| when |result| is NOT

net::OK are also fixed.

* network::SimpleHostResolver returns net::ERR_FAILED on pipe break as

opposed to the HostResolver used in network_diagnostics (that returns

net::ERR_CONNECTION_FAILED). The affected tests are also updated to

reflect this difference.

entry.title: AutofillProfile Sync: Don't distinguish between (un)verified profiles.
entry.content:
The concept of verified profiles is about to be removed from Autofill.

See the doc linked in the bug for context. This CL removes any logic in

the AutofillProfile Sync code that becomes irrelevant due to this

change.



In particular, the Sync logic currently discards any updates to verified

profiles from an unverified profile. In order to eventually remove the

origin completely, this is dropped. See [1].



Roughly, the idea is the following: Before explicit save prompts,

profiles were silently imported/updated. These profiles were considered

unverified profiles. Profiles created through the settings were

considered verified. Verified profiles should never be updated

silently with information from an unverified profile.

Sync-side, the when merging local and remote profiles, the current

implementation ensures that verified profiles are never changed by

unverified ones. This CL removes this logic and all related tests.



[1] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1qIUjKcC7uotwOoXil3xyweHqLKNV9Hw0xXxyXc25JPs/edit#bookmark=id.17u19py2z2rm

entry.title: First implementation of superrulesets.
entry.content:
When the new flag CSSSuperRulesets is on, we may choose to merge all of

the active RuleSets for this scope into a superruleset, containing all

of the rules. This can be cheaper to match against than doing each of

them separately, since we get fewer hash table lookups and similar --

but it can also have a cost in terms of memory and time to build the

superruleset.



Currently, our implementation is primitive; this is so that we can

send it out to Finch and get a feeling for what gains and/or problems

we see in the wild. In particular, these are directions we consider

exploring:



- Destroying old RuleSets after merging them into a superruleset,

saving on RAM.

- Starting from the largest RuleSet, instead of an empty one

(which would save on merging time in the fairly common case

where there is one large RuleSet carrying the majority of the rules).

In particular, this would help initial style by a few (1‚Äì2)

percentage points in the benchmarks below.

- Blocklisting modified RuleSets, so that if one style sheet gets

frequently modified, it won't trigger creating superrulesets

over and over again. (But note that already today, we merge

all the rule _feature_ sets, i.e., invalidation sets, every time.)

entry.title: Fix TestUrlRequestCallback.setBlockOnTerminalState()
entry.content:
Currently, the following code doesn't do what one would expect:



testUrlRequestCallback.setBlockOnTerminalState(false);

testUrlRequestCallback.blockForDone();



The second call will return immediately instead of waiting for the

done callback to run. This is because setBlockOnTerminalState() and

blockForDone() are both implemented using the same condition variable

(`mDone`) and end up interfering with each other.



The current code is also quite confusing because the semantics of

`mDone` is to block until the done callback fires, but

`setBlockOnTerminalState` is repurposing `mDone` to mean something

different, i.e. to block until we want the done callback to return. This

cannot end well.



This commit fixes the issue by introducing a separate condition variable

to prevent these TestUrlRequestCallback features from interfering with

each other.

entry.title: [WebAuthn] Allow multiple attempts at Android Conditional UI
entry.content:
Currently a conditional UI GetAssertion request on Android is resolved if a user selects a credential and then dismisses the user

verification (PIN entry or biometric) without authorizing it. This is inconsistent with desktop behaviour, which allows the user to select

the credential again from autofill UI and restart the sign-in flow.



This CL matches Android behaviour to desktop.



Summary of the changes:

- The native code uses a RepeatingCallback rather than a OnceCallback

so selections can be made multiple times without disrupting

native-side state.

- When an error is received in the response from a Get Intent, and a

conditional UI request is in progress, it is logged and ignored.

The WebAuthn request is not completed, so the native side can

cause another intent to be created and dispatched. An exception

is if the request was aborted by the RP while the GMSCore UI was

being displayed to the user. Then the request closes with ABORT_ERROR.

- Get request abort is refactored. The call to 'cancelRequest' has

been changed to 'cleanupRequest', and clears the callback without

invoking it. It has to be called at the completion of all

conditional UI requests, successful or not.

- A reference to RenderFrameHost is cached in Fido2CredentialRequest,

since it has to be available for cleanupRequest later. This removes

the need to pass it as an argument to private methods.

entry.title: [iOS][byot] Move bottom message view out of the regular tabs grid view
entry.content:
Previously, the regular tabs bottom message is owned by the grid view

controller for regular tabs. This was designed since both were only

shown when the user was on the regular tab grid, but since the display

and position of the bottom message is really controlled by the tab grid

view controller, weird animation issues would happen.



This CL puts the bottom message back into the tab grid view controller

instead of the GridViewController for the regular tabs, and fixes

animation bugs in the process. Bugs fixed:



1. Tapping "incognito" and "remote" buttons not working when the

prompt is visible, because "viewDidLayoutSubviews" would "scroll" the

page back to regular.

2. Closing tabs from when the tabs are more than the screen could hold

to when the tabs would not fill the tab grid screen would NOT hide the

bottom message. This issue used to happen because the offset of the

grid view controller doesn't seem to be updating properly. (Actually

the exact root cause is not identified yet.)
